North Korea Completely Rejects Untrusted Unilateral Disarmament
North Korea’s foreign minister told the U.N. on Saturday that maintaining sanctions was fueling the country’s mistrust of the U.S., which in those circumstances would have absolutely refused to unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho said at the World Organization General Assembly that North Korea had taken "important goodwill measures" over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the site for nuclear tests, and committing to the non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"We do not see any consistent response from the United States," he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no security in our national security, and under these circumstances we absolutely refuse to disarm unilaterally first.”
Although Ri has re-used the well-known complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” denuclearization with which North Korea would be rewarded on the basis of gradual actions, his statement was important because he did not completely reject unilateral denuclearization as previously done by Pyongyang.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump during the first absolute meeting between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader, held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work toward the “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump promised assurances of North Korean security.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also opposed calls to ease tough international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
"The US insists on the need to 'have a denuclearization first' and to increase the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve their purpose in a coercive manner and even opposes the 'declaration of an end to the war,'" Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an illusion of those who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the continuation of sanctions is increasing our distrust.”
Ri did not refer to plans for a second meeting between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader announced at the UN earlier this week.
The minister instead stressed the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the last 5 months and added: "If the counterpart of this issue of denuclearization was South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be at this point dead."
But even so, Ri’s tone of speech was markedly different from last year’s speech at the UN General Assembly, when he stated that it was inevitable to target U.S. territory with North Korean missiles after “the president of evil” Trump had called Kim a “missile man” engaged in a suicide mission.
In front of the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to “completely destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in embarking on the path of disarmament, but said there was still much to be done and that sanctions would remain in place until North Korea’s denuclearization.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not have a deadline, stating that "if it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter."
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the actions it has taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that "compliance with Security Council sanctions must continue with force and without exception until complete, final and assured denuclearization is achieved."
The Security Council unanimously endorsed sanctions control of North Korea in 2006 in an attempt to stifle funding for nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again the following month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but the last trip did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July claiming that progress had been made, but a few hours later North Korea accused him of filing "gangster demands."
North Korea had pledged during a meeting this month with Moon to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the US had taken “compliant measures.”
He said Kim had explained to him that the “compliant measures” he wanted were security assurances Trump had committed himself to in Singapore and actions toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has pushed all of its students to sleep longer in an attempt to counter the growing male culture of studying for entire caffeine-fueled nights.
A university scholar has found that students at the world’s number one university often have no idea of the basic concepts of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He had the idea to start the course after a lecture he had given on the impact of lack of sleep on learning.
“In the end a girl came to me and said, ‘Why am I being told this only now, when I’m in my senior year?’
She said that no one had ever told her anything about the importance of sleep, which surprised me very much,” she told The Telegraph.
The course, given for the first time this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep-related habits can help academic and athletic performance, as well as improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the university’s director general of health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were suffering from a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive activities.
In one section there is the image of a dorm room, where students can select coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books to be able to know the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is influenced by lack of sleep, and the importance of an evening routine.
In another section, participants are explained how lack of long-term sleep can increase the risks of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, therefore encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that it will not immediately change the behavior of students.
But we believe they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes,” added Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of pride linked to the “white night to study” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students lead to a lack of sleep being a growing problem.
Sleeping enough and having a good quality sleep should be the students' "secret weapon" to fight stress, fatigue, anxiety, explained and even should serve to avoid fattening since lack of sleep brings the brain into sleepless mode, making people constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student enrolled in the faculty of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler develop the course, after taking one of his lessons last year during his first year at Harvard.
He explained that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course aimed at the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, will be to ask all graduate students to follow a similar study program before enrolling in this competitive institute.
Professor Czeisler advised students to set an alarm for when they need to go to bed, as well as when they need to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can tilt the circadian rhythm, leading to sleep problems.
