World Wide Web Inventor Plans to Launch a New Internet to Challenge Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a startup that seeks to rival Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company that draws its origins from the solid open source platform of Berners-Lee.
Solid allows users to choose where to store their data and what people can access and what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intent behind Inrupt is to "dominate the world".
“We have to do it now,” he said of the startup.
"It's a historic moment."
The app uses Solid technology to allow people to create their own “online personal data store” or a POD.
It can include lists of contacts, things to do, calendars, music libraries, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack, and Spotify were all available on one browser at a time.
The uniqueness of the online personal data warehouse is that it is completely up to the user to choose who can have access to what type of information.
The company calls it “personal empowerment through data.”
The idea for Inrupt, according to John Bruce, the company’s CEO, is to bring adequate resources, processes and skills to make Solid accessible to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some developers in the staff hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology programmers around the world will be able to bring their decentralized apps to life using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team will not tell Facebook and Google whether or not to introduce a complete change where their business models are completely wiped out overnight.
“We’re not asking for their permission.”
In a Medium post on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that “Inrupt’s mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem that help protect the integrity and quality of the new web built from Solid.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate on net neutrality.
Even after the launch of Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the Founder and Director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m incredibly optimistic about this new era of the web,” Berners-Lee added.
Bernard Vann: Commemorated the Ecclesiastical of the Great War with Victoria Cross
The only Church of England clergyman to be awarded a Victoria Cross during World War I as a fighter was commemorated in his hometown after 100 years.
The Lieutenant Colonel, Reverend Bernard Vann, gained recognition on 29 September 1918 in the attack on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
However, four days later he was killed by a sniper and he never knew he had achieved the highest level of British military honor.
On Saturday at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire, her two grandchildren inaugurated a memorial plaque.
One of his grandsons, Michael Vann, said it was “magnifyingly symbolic” that the stone would be inaugurated exactly 100 years after his grandfather’s award-winning prowess.
According to the London Gazette, on 29 September 1918 Lieutenant Colonel Van led his battalion across the Canal Saint-Quentin "through a very thick fog, under the heavy fire of the camp and the war machines".
He then rushed towards the line of fire and with the "greatest gallantry" advanced the line before running with a single-handed cannon and landing three of the detachment.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918 - just a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather’s actions were “something I know I can never live up to and something that makes me more humble.”
He and his brother, Dr. James Vann, also laid a wreath after the parade, conducted by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said he "felt really honored to play a role in the parade" and added "the value of a true hero is demonstrated by the support that will be given to him by so many people."
