Desert Island Discs: Tom Daley felt "lower" because of sexuality
Olympic swimmer Tom Daley says he grew up feeling inferior to anyone because of his sexuality – but this gave him the motivation to succeed.
The 24-year-old said he didn’t realize, until he got to high school, that “not everyone is like me.”
Speaking in the first episode of Desert Island Discs on Radio 4, presented by Lauren Laverne, he said he had made his voice heard about gay rights to give "hope" to others.
He also said that being a parent made him less interested in winning the Olympics.
The usual presenter of the old-time program, Kirsty Young, took a series of months off for illness.
Presenting himself as an outcast in Laverne's first program, Daley said he felt "less than" anyone else as he grew up because "it was not socially acceptable that he liked both boys and girls."
He said, “Today, the feeling of feeling less of, and feeling different, were the things that really gave me the strength and energy to succeed.”
He wanted to try to be “something,” he said, so as not to disappoint anyone if they accidentally discovered his sexuality.
The two-time bronze medallist at the Olympics has become a high-profile LGBT activist and used his face at this year’s Australian Commonwealth Games to appeal to more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said he made his voice heard because he felt lucky to be able to live openly without consequences and wanted to give “hope” to others.
The three-time world champion said that the fact that he fell in love with a man - the American director Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013 - "took me by surprise".
Daley married the Oscar winner, who is 20 years older than him last year, but said the age difference was never a problem.
"When so many of them passed away at a young age" - he went to his first Olympics when he was 14 and his father died of cancer three years later - he said it was hard to find someone of the same age who had experienced similar ups and downs.
The two became parents in June, of a child named Robert Ray Black-Daley, and Daley said his "whole perspective" has changed.
“If you asked me last year, it was all about the fact that I had to win a gold medal,” he said.
“You know one thing, there are more important things than Olympic gold medals.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie.”
His son bears the same name as his father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said his father had not accepted the fact that he was about to die and that one of the last things he asked was if they already had tickets to London 2012 - because he wanted to be in the front row.
“I couldn’t tell him, ‘You’re not going to be here to be in the front row, Dad,’” he said.
“I was holding his hand when he stopped breathing and until he actually stopped and died, I still hadn’t realized he wasn’t invincible,” he said.
The following year Daley competed in the 2012 Olympics, winning bronze.
“I just knew it was what I had dreamed of all my life – swimming in front of a home audience at the Olympics, there was no better feeling,” he said.
This also inspired the choice of his first song - Proud by Heather Small - which had a special meaning for him in preparation for the Olympics and still makes him come out as a goose.
Desert Island Discs is on BBC Radio 4 on Sunday at 11:15 BST.
The out-of-form Mickelson put on the bench in the Ryder Cup on Saturday
American Phil Mickelson will set a record Sunday when he plays his 47th Ryder Cup game, but will have to get back in shape to avoid becoming an unfortunate milestone.
Mickelson, playing in the biennial event for a twelfth time as a record, was benched by Captain Jim Furyk for Saturday's fourballs and foursomes.
Instead of being at the center of the action, as was often the case for the United States, the five-time champion spent the day between cheerleading and working on his own game in the range, hoping to correct what torments him.
Having never been the strongest of drivers even at the peak of his career, the 48-year-old is not the ideal choice for the difficult Le Golf National, where the bumpy course regularly punishes the wrong shots.
And if the path itself was not discouraging enough, Mickelson, in Sunday’s ninth match, faces the accurate British Open champion Francesco Molinari, who collaborated with newcomer Tommy Fleetwood to win all four of their matches this week.
If the Americans, four points below at the start of their 12 singles matches, start with a scorching start, Mickelson’s match could prove absolutely crucial.
