The National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
New research conducted at a Scottish Highlands estate aims to reveal how bats use their sight to procure food.
It is hoped that the findings could shed light on the behavior of the only existing flying mammals and guide future protective activities.
The National Trust for Scotland scientists’ study will follow common bats and sopranos, as well as brown ears and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens, Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations around the property to track bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations using portable detectors.
Analyses of the sounds recorded by an expert will determine the frequency of bat calls and how each species behaves.
They will then produce a habitat map and a report to create a detailed picture on the scale of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation consultant for the NTS, hopes the findings could reveal which areas of habitat are most important for bats and how these are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as grassland creation, and how to best maintain bat forests and other related species.
The population of bats in Scotland and the United Kingdom has declined significantly over the past century.
Bats are at risk due to construction and development work involving trespoli and ruining habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a threat, as can flypaper and some chemical treatments of building materials, in addition to domestic cat attacks.
The bats are not really blind.
However, due to their night-hunting habits, their ears are more useful than the eyes when it comes to grabbing a prey.
They use a sophisticated eco-localization technique to identify insects and obstacles on their trajectory.
The NTS, responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
Ten qualified experts regularly conduct investigations, inspect the trespoli and sometimes perform rescues.
The organisation has even set up Scotland's first bat-only reserve at the Threeave estate in the Dumfries and Galloway region, which hosts eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The estate manager, David Thompson, says the property is the ideal territory.
"Here at Threeave we have a vast area for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, many secular trees and a good habitat.
But there’s a lot about bats that we don’t know yet, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us understand more about their growth needs.”
It stresses the importance of controlling bats before conducting maintenance within the properties as it is possible that the involuntary destruction of a single maternal trespolo could kill up to 400 females and small ones, perhaps wiping out an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, annoy, disturb or destroy their trefoils.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
“We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we don’t know how their populations go about it.”
