Brexit: The UK will regret the loss of car manufacturers forever
The UK “may regret forever” the loss of its status as a world leader in car manufacturing following Brexit, Industry Minister Greg Clark said.
He added that he was "concerned" about Toyota UK's statements to the BBC regarding Britain's possible exit from the EU without a deal and the resulting temporary shutdown of production at the factory in Burnaston, near Derby.
"We need an agreement," said Minister Clark.
The Japanese automaker claims that delays at the borders, in the event of a no-deal Brexit, could affect jobs.
The factory in Burnaston, where the Toyota Auris and Avensis are built, produced about 150,000 cars last year, 90% of which were exported to the rest of the European Union.
"I believe that if Britain leaves the EU at the end of March, production at our factory will stop," said Marvin Cooke, Toyota's general manager in Burnaston.
There is growing concern in other UK carmakers about leaving the EU without a cross-border trade deal, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover.
BMW, for example, claims that after Brexit it will close its Mini plants in Oxford for a month.
The main concern concerns the risks in the supply chain encountered by manufacturers in the event of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota’s production line is run on the basis of the “just in time” concept, with parts arriving every 37 minutes from UK and European suppliers for custom cars.
If the UK leaves the EU without a deal on 29 March, border disruptions could cause delays and lack of parties.
It would be impossible for Toyota to hold more than a day’s worth of inventory at its Derbyshire plant, the company said, so production would be halted.
Minister Clark argues that Theresa May’s plan for future relations with the EU is “precisely thought out to avoid these inconveniences at the borders.”
"We need a deal. We want to have the best deal that will allow us to not only enjoy the current success but to seize this opportunity," he told BBC Radio 4's Today programme.
“The proof, not only from Toyota but also from other car manufacturers, is that we absolutely have to be able to continue what has been a very successful distribution chain.”
Toyota has not been able to say how long production could stop but, in the long run, warns that additional costs could reduce plant competitiveness and potentially jobs.
Peter Tsouvallaris, who has worked in Burnaston for 24 years and is in charge of the plant’s trade union delegates, says workers are deeply concerned: “Based on my experience, once jobs are reduced, they are no longer reintegrated.”
A government spokesman said: “We have proposed a precise and credible plan for future relations with the EU.”
Trump’s meeting with Rosenstein could be postponed again, the White House says.
Donald Trump’s high-risk meeting with Deputy Attorney General Rod Rosenstein could be “rescheduled for a week” as the dispute over Judge Brett Kavanaugh continues, the White House said on Sunday.
Rosenstein oversees the work of special counsel Robert Mueller who investigates Russian interference in the election, the ties between Trump’s advisers and Russia, and the president’s eventual obstruction of justice.
