The move will be seen as an attempt to neutralize the success of Jeremy Corbyn’s initiative to attract young voters with the promise of providing more affordable housing and higher incomes.
The increase in the stamp duty will be applied to individuals and companies that do not pay taxes in the UK, and the additional resources will support the government's initiative to combat the homeless phenomenon.
The surcharge, which is in addition to the current stamp duty, including the high levels introduced two years ago on second homes and buy to lets properties (purchased for rent), could amount to more than 3%.
