They played better than us.”
Red tide update: concentration decreases in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in red tide concentration in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, patchy flowering conditions, which suggest a decrease in concentration, are evident in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties.
The red tide bloom extends for about 130 miles of coastline from the north of Pinellas County to the south of Lee County.
The piazzas are located about 10 miles off Hillsborough County but in fewer areas than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week an average concentration was reported in Pinellas County or off its coasts, a concentration from low to high concentration off the coast of Hillsborough County, from a bottom concentration to a high concentration in Manatee County, from a bottom concentration to a high concentration in Sarasota County or off its coasts, from a concentration of high concentration on the coast to a concentration on the coast.
Cases of respiratory irritation continue to be reported in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
Last week, no cases were reported in northwest Florida.
